  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Silk Without the Workload" imageAlt="Japanese Chin puppy having its silky single coat brushed" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Chin's coat looks like a commitment and isn't, which is the pleasant surprise of the breed. It's a single coat with no undercoat: brush twice a week, watch the trousers and ear fringes for the occasional tangle, and it dries quickly after rainy-day walks. There's no mandatory salon schedule, though many owners book a tidy-up every couple of months. The dog itself does some of the work, that self-grooming habit is real.</p>
      <p>The daily ten-second habit is the eyes: large, prominent, and the breed's most delicate feature, they deserve a gentle wipe and a quick check every day. Anything squinty or weepy gets a vet look the same week. The wipes are in your starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Chin Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Japanese Chin puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Chin goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Chin health points worth knowing: the flat face brings mild brachycephalic traits, so soft snoring is standard equipment but laboured breathing after gentle activity is a vet visit; the prominent eyes scratch more easily than most breeds' and get the daily check above; heart murmurs appear in some lines in later life, worth including in the annual vet listen from middle age; and patellar luxation, the standard small-breed kneecap issue.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. Keep the Chin lean; extra weight loads a short airway. See the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Living Flat-Faced in Singapore: The Heat Rules" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>The Chin wears a milder version of the flat face than a Pug, and the rules don't soften with it, because Singapore doesn't. Dogs cool themselves by panting; a short-muzzled dog pants inefficiently, and our island sits at 30-plus degrees with tropical humidity most of the year.</p>
      <p>The rules: walks before 9am or after 6pm, gentle ones, which suits this breed's appetite anyway; shade and water on every outing; a cool, ventilated room through the afternoon; and know the emergency signs: relentless heavy panting, a very dark red tongue, wobbliness. Cool water on the body, aircon, and the vet, in that order.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">The heat rules</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Gentle walks, cool hours only',
            'Fan or aircon through the afternoon',
            'Keep it lean; weight loads the airway',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M20 6 9 17l-5-5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Chin's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Japanese Chin puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Chin surveys the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm, cool and unhurried. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, gentle handling, and no pressure; the Chin settles on its own schedule and rewards patience with early trust.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, the first perch is claimed, and, if you're lucky, the first Chin spin debuts. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; see what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

